WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:02.480
As people interested in geography and nature,

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:06.320
it is usually quite easy to nail a&nbsp;
countries’ or region’s geography with

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:13.440
a single word. Switzerland? Mountains.&nbsp;
Qatar? Desert. And Borneo? Rainforest.

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:17.440
But doing the same exercise for the&nbsp;
Golden State of the US, California,

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:22.400
too many beautiful and dramatic landscapes,&nbsp;
national parks, mountains, deserts and coastlines

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:27.680
are popping up, so perhaps the only correct&nbsp;
word to describe its geography is diversity.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:31.360
To truly appreciate California’s&nbsp;
incredible scale and variety,

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:35.680
let’s embark on an all encompassing journey&nbsp;
around the Central Valley, beginning in the

00:00:35.680 --> 00:00:40.480
Colorado Desert where the sands of the Sonoran&nbsp;
desert are crossing the Mexican border.

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:45.760
Chapter 1: Colorado Desert
Characterized by extreme aridity,

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:51.200
the Colorado Desert is the classic image of&nbsp;
the wild west. Dry scrublands and sandstone

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:56.160
monoliths are standing in front of a dramatic&nbsp;
mountain backdrop in almost every direction.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:00.160
While the Colorado River, which lends its&nbsp;
name to the desert, only flows along the

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:04.960
eastern flanks where it marks the state border&nbsp;
to Arizona, it has actually had a significant

00:01:04.960 --> 00:01:10.400
impact on the desert’s history and geography.
Approximately 90% of the water which makes it

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:16.560
to the Imperial dam of the Colorado River is being&nbsp;
diverted into the Imperial and Coachella Valleys,

00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:22.480
supplying 100 miles of lush fields with irrigation&nbsp;
water and mocking mother nature in the meantime.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.520
Since the early 20th century, three major canals&nbsp;
have carried the Colorado River water across

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:33.200
the desert but such defiance of the natural&nbsp;
order doesn’t come without its consequences.

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:38.960
As a result of a dam breach over a century ago,&nbsp;
the man-made Salton Sea has formed in the center

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:44.000
of the valley, which has since been kept alive&nbsp;
by excess canal water and irrigation runoff.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.880
Since this water is contaminated from the&nbsp;
farming runoff, a crust of salts, trace

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:53.840
metals and pesticides is now surrounding the lake&nbsp;
shore and the winds blowing across the valley can

00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:59.920
sometimes make these pollutants airborne, creating&nbsp;
hazardous dust storms. Luckily though, at 72

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:06.320
meters or 236 feet below sea level and surrounded&nbsp;
by mountains, the valley’s geography helps shield

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:12.880
the neighboring Mojave Desert from these problems.
Chapter 2: Mojave Desert

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:18.720
Behind the Joshua Tree National Park to the north,&nbsp;
the second major desert of California opens up and

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:23.360
even though they are in such close proximity,&nbsp;
there are some very distinct differences.

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:28.160
Although only a thin mountain range separates&nbsp;
the two deserts, the rain shadow effect from

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:33.200
the Sierra Nevada and Transverse Ranges is&nbsp;
much stronger in the Mojave. This can be seen

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:38.160
with the summer monsoon clouds for example,&nbsp;
which come in through the Gulf of California

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:43.360
and provide the occasional rainfall to the&nbsp;
Sonoran Desert. With the Orocopia and Little

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:48.720
San Bernardino mountains in the way however,&nbsp;
not even these clouds reach the Mojave Desert.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:53.120
While areas south of the mountains&nbsp;
receive around 200 mm of rain annually,

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:59.040
the core of the Mojave Desert gets as little&nbsp;
as 40, so vegetation becomes even more sparse here.

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:05.520
Mainly the Joshua Tree thrives at the deserts&nbsp;
elevations between 600 to 1,200 meters but despite

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:11.200
this elevation, dramatic mountainscapes tower&nbsp;
along the horizon almost everywhere you look.

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:15.680
Especially in the northern half, these ridges&nbsp;
typically run in a northerly-southernly direction,

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:21.600
where millions of years of tectonic stretching&nbsp;
and faulting have built the up to 3350 meter

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:27.040
or 11.000 feet tall mountains, while&nbsp;
also sinking the adjoining desert floor.&nbsp;

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:33.040
The dramatic landscape creates pockets of intense&nbsp;
aridity, where salt flats and alluvial fans from

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:38.640
ancient lakes make the land even more forbidding.&nbsp;
Well over 100 years ago, the village of Furnace

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:43.600
Creek actually experienced the highest natural&nbsp;
temperature ever recorded on planet earth, where

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:52.880
on a fateful Thursday afternoon, the temperature&nbsp;
rose to 56.7 °C or 134.1 °F. By then, the valley

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:57.360
was already known as Death Valley and the National&nbsp;
Park which has been established around it in the

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:02.480
late 20th century doesn’t just contain the hottest&nbsp;
place on earth, but also the lowest depression of

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:08.880
the continent. Sitting another 14 meters below&nbsp;
the shores of Salton Sea, Badwater Basin reaches

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:14.800
a low point of 86 meters below sea level,&nbsp;
making Death Valley a place of true extremes.

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:17.920
But the mountains surrounding it also hold their own records.

00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:22.960
Chapter 3: The Sierra Nevada
Just 130 kilometers west of this

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:28.800
extreme point, the Sierra Nevada Mountains are&nbsp;
reaching for the opposite extreme. Demarcating

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:33.680
the western flank of the Mojave Desert and&nbsp;
extending all the way into northern California,

00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:38.000
the Sierra Nevada are drawing the eastern&nbsp;
wall around the Central Valley and within

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.680
this massive mountain range, the tallest summit of&nbsp;
the contiguous United States soars in the clouds.

00:04:43.680 --> 00:04:50.880
The extremely jagged ridge line of Mount&nbsp;
Whitney stands at 14500 feet or 4420 meters

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:55.680
above sea level and is caused by a massive block&nbsp;
of granite that is anchored in the surrounding

00:04:55.680 --> 00:05:00.160
fault system penetrating the surface.
The mountain range as a whole extends

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:06.960
for 640 kilometers or 400 miles north to south&nbsp;
and next to Mount Whitney houses an additional

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:12.640
11 fourteeners, meaning mountain peaks above&nbsp;
14.000 feet in elevation, easily putting the

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:18.640
state into S Tier for high alpine mountaineering,&nbsp;
alongside Colorado, Washington and Alaska. Yet,

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:23.520
perhaps the most famous aspect of the Sierra&nbsp;
Nevada is not its peaks, but the vast forests

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:27.600
that fill its valleys and slopes.
From Sequoia National Park in the

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:33.440
south to the Sierra, Stanislaus, Tahoe,&nbsp;
Plumas, and Lassen National Forests,

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:38.240
these valleys and granite outcrops are home&nbsp;
to some of the world’s most remarkable trees.

00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:43.280
The most famous of these is easily the General&nbsp;
Sherman in the Sequoia National Park. Standing

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:48.160
at a proud height of 84 meters, and&nbsp;
with a circumference of 31 meters,

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:53.520
it is the most voluminous tree on the planet, but&nbsp;
the records don’t stop here. A different specimen

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:58.720
of the same species just a couple of miles to&nbsp;
the east holds the record for the thickest limbs,

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:04.080
while a Bristlecone Pine in the Inyo National&nbsp;
Forest has sprouted its roots over 4800 years

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:09.760
ago in the center of the White Mountains, making&nbsp;
it the oldest currently living tree in the world.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:14.480
Staying within the topic of geographic records,&nbsp;
straddling the border between California and

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:21.440
Nevada, Lake Tahoe is the largest alpine lake of&nbsp;
North America, and with a basin depth of 501 meters

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:27.440
its volume only falls short of the Great Lakes.&nbsp;
Having reached the upper third of California now,

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:32.000
and being surrounded by an alpine topography,&nbsp;
the climate has shifted dramatically from

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.960
the southerly deserts, and the annual climate&nbsp;
graph is more comparable to temperate European

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:41.840
climates found in the Netherlands or northern&nbsp;
Germany with one very noticeable difference.

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:46.800
While temperatures and precipitation is nearly&nbsp;
identical, the annual snowfall is one of the

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:53.120
highest in the world when comparing it to other&nbsp;
populated places and the 180 inches or 4.5 meter

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:58.720
of snow actually far exceed the snowiest&nbsp;
major cites of Canada by almost a meter.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:03.360
This climate has turned the mountains around&nbsp;
Lake Tahoe into a winter sports hotspot and

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:07.840
sets the tone for what we can expect&nbsp;
around California’s northernmost region. Bringing us to

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:14.320
Chapter 4: The Northern Mountains
As the tall ridges of the Sierra Nevada fade, the

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:20.560
high elevation stays, forming the 1.000.000 acre&nbsp;
large Modoc Plateau. Looking at a rock type map

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:26.160
of California, a drastic shift takes place here&nbsp;
with the old Metamorphic Rock of the Sierra Nevada

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:31.840
being replaced by young Igneous rock spanning&nbsp;
the whole northeastern corner of the state.

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:35.680
Metamorphic here means that the rock has&nbsp;
formed out of previous rock through pressure

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:40.480
and chemical processes, while igneous rock&nbsp;
can be considered as “1st generation” rock

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:45.920
from magma which has protruded earth's surface.&nbsp;
The pyroclastic fragments and tuff beds across

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:50.800
the volcanic tableland are another visual proof&nbsp;
of this shift, and the influence of volcanoes

00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:55.760
becomes even more pronounced as we head west.
Rising on the western flanks of the highlands,

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:58.960
the southernmost extent of the Cascade Range&nbsp;
forms a significant boundary between the Pacific

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:03.920
coast and the interior of the United States,&nbsp;
housing some of the US’s most famous volcanoes

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:08.880
like Mount Saint Helens, Mount Rainier,&nbsp;
or Mount Hood in Oregon and Washington.

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:13.120
The Californian section also has some impressive&nbsp;
features to offer though with the flanks of

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:17.920
its tallest active stratovolcano Mount Shasta&nbsp;
accommodating two massive glacial arms hugging

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:23.360
the mountain. While Global warming is usually&nbsp;
a slow but certain death sentence to glaciers,

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:28.960
the Whitney and Hotlum Glaciers seem to defy the&nbsp;
norm here. Despite rising temperatures over the past

00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:33.680
150 years, increased snowfall has allowed&nbsp;
the Whitney and Hotlum Glaciers to grow,

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:38.160
making them among the few glaciers&nbsp;
worldwide that are currently expanding.

00:08:38.160 --> 00:08:42.080
The mechanism responsible for these&nbsp;
stratovolcanoes scattering the landscape

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:46.080
is the Cascadia Subduction Zone, just&nbsp;
offshore of the Klamath Mountains,

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:51.120
the neighbouring mountain range to the west.
Deep underground, a triple junction of the Gorda,

00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:56.880
Pacific and North American tectonic plate has&nbsp;
created a highly unstable environment. All three

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:01.680
plates are moving into different directions,&nbsp;
creating a network of subduction and transform

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:06.960
faults where tectonic friction is building up a&nbsp;
long overdue thrust, which will eventually shake

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:12.960
up the region. The last large earthquake here has been&nbsp;
over 300 years ago now and regular small tremors

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:17.680
are possibly foreshadowing what is to come.
From the triple junction near Eureka,

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:21.840
the world-famous San Andreas Fault marks&nbsp;
the boundary between the Pacific and North

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:26.240
American plates, leading us to the final&nbsp;
major mountain range of our journey and to

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:31.280
Chapter 5: The Coastal Ranges
Drawing an arc through the State

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:36.240
of California, the San Andreas Fault is&nbsp;
a massive transform boundary which has

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:40.240
been the cause for countless earthquakes&nbsp;
but also largescale uplift of the land

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:44.800
across its 800 mile or 1200 kilometer&nbsp;
extent to the Gulf of California.

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:49.120
Running along the San Andreas’ eastern&nbsp;
edge, the Coastal Ranges are forming the

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:53.920
final enclosure to the central valley and the&nbsp;
two constituting sub ranges in the north and

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:58.720
south slowly transition the climate back to&nbsp;
the aridity that our journey started with.

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:04.000
Within the northern range, an east-west division&nbsp;
is marked by the Eel and Russian River which

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.480
occupy the broad valley in between them and&nbsp;
several valley pockets are nestled throughout

00:10:08.480 --> 00:10:13.360
the heavily forested mountain slopes. Many&nbsp;
of these are filled with the snow runoff of

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:18.720
the surrounding summits and the largest one of&nbsp;
these, called Clear Lake, occupies an elevated

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:24.480
basin at around 420 meters above the sea level.&nbsp;
According to the US Geological Survey, which has

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:29.520
extensively analyzed the sediment core samples of the&nbsp;
lake bottom in the 70s, this lake is actually the

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:34.640
oldest lake of the North American Continent.
Resting on stable bedrock and maintaining

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:39.280
a delicate balance between sedimentation&nbsp;
and subsidence, Clear Lake has held water

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:46.000
continuously for an astonishing 475,000 years now.
The only outflow of this lake directs the water

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:50.400
towards the east, where it merges with nearly&nbsp;
all other streams that find their way into

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:56.000
the central valley. And once the main stems of the&nbsp;
Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers are combined,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
they find a gap between the Northern and&nbsp;
Southern Coastal Range, and fill a massive

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.560
basin between the mountain ranges.
The entire system spans 90 kilometers North

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:10.320
to South and over 70 kilometers from the River&nbsp;
mouths to San Francisco’s Golden Gate Bridge,

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:15.440
which marks the boundary to the Pacific Ocean.
This far-spanning wetland was once part of Lake

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:20.160
Corcoran, an ancient lake which occupied&nbsp;
the central valley. Once tectonic shifts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:23.920
and erosion broke through the Golden&nbsp;
Gate however, the whole section turned

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:28.640
into a river bed which drained the lake.
During the ice ages, shifting sea levels

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:34.160
repeatedly transformed the region from dry plain&nbsp;
to estuary, leading to today’s shallow bay, where

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:39.760
most areas outside the main channel are just a few&nbsp;
meters deep. These shallow shore areas now host

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:46.000
mudflats that are vital to the Pacific Flyway,&nbsp;
supporting millions of migratory birds each year.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.400
On both sides of the San Francisco Bay, behind&nbsp;
the headquarters of the most influential tech

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:54.800
companies in the world, the Californian Coastal&nbsp;
Ranges continue their parallel ridges all the

00:11:54.800 --> 00:12:00.400
way down to California's most populous city. The&nbsp;
climate here shifts again from the warm mediterranean

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:04.560
climate of northern and central California,&nbsp;
back to the aridity which has defined the

00:12:04.560 --> 00:12:09.600
deserts from the beginning of our journey.&nbsp;
A total of 18.5 million people spread over

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:15.120
13 cities surpassing the 100.000 inhabitants&nbsp;
mark, are settled in the Los Angeles Basin

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:20.880
which is surrounded by mountains and the Pacific&nbsp;
Ocean on all sides. From the southern outskirts,

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:25.840
it is a mere 1 hour drive past the Little San&nbsp;
Bernardino Mountains for us to have come full

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:30.960
circle around California, and we are back&nbsp;
in the desert heat of the Coachella Valley.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:36.400
As a whole, California is a true epitome of&nbsp;
geographical diversity. Covering everything from

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:42.480
the snowiest mountains to the driest valleys,&nbsp;
from lush forests to prosperous wetlands,

00:12:42.480 --> 00:12:48.880
from active stratovolcanoes to Salt Lakes and the&nbsp;
most influential metropolitan areas in the world.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:53.840
I hope you enjoyed this roundtrip through what&nbsp;
I consider the most exciting state in the US.

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:56.800
If you want to learn more about&nbsp;
California's neighbour to the east,

00:12:56.800 --> 00:13:02.000
I can recommend this one about the Geography&nbsp;
of the Rocky Mountains, or watch what youtube thinks is

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.440
best for you here. And if you want to further&nbsp;
